english:
  title: A Record of the Fortress Construction at Happo
  author: Lee Cham
  language: eng
  text: |-
    The four gates of the fortress were completed. Minister Pae requested that I write a record of it. I demurred, saying, "Happo is a great military garrison, and building this fortress is indeed a magnificent undertaking. Such a record requires the seasoned hand of a master writer. I must respectfully decline." The Minister replied, "These days, whenever officials undertake construction projects, they send letters seeking records, invariably troubling those of high station to embellish their names with fine words. I shall not do so. Since you are well acquainted with this work, why not record its beginning and end for posterity?" Thus I could not refuse.

    In former times, the garrison burned in a military conflict, and soldiers were left to camp in the fields. The Recorder Cao, searching for auspicious ground, found a suitable site. In the spring of the year Dingsi, the Administrator Yu began construction there, but soon was recalled to the capital. Minister Pae, appointed Deputy Commander, took charge of the troops. Upon arriving, he restored and repaired the military camp. When the work was finished, he addressed his men: "Now that the camp is built, shall we delay building walls? We call a military garrison a bastion because it shields the realm. How can a bastion that cannot protect itself be worthy of the name? Consider a man with a home in the mountains—if he does not build high fences and set traps, how can he defend against wild beasts? Or a man dwelling in the city—if he does not raise strong walls and secure his gates, how can he guard against thieves who breach walls? Even a rustic farmer understands this much.

    "In the four years past, we have moved our camp three times. This is because, lacking outer walls, we could not fix our people's resolve. I wish to build walls here—deep moats and high ramparts to guard against unforeseen calamity. What say you?" All the officers and soldiers replied, "We have followed your command long, yet our wisdom is shallow and we lack such foresight. We place ourselves entirely in your hands."

    The Minister then issued proclamations, gathered the people, prepared tools and materials, consulted with nearby and distant counties, and directed the work to begin. Considering that earthen walls crumble easily while brick walls demand excessive labor, but stone walls stand firm and require less effort, he chose to build with stone. When the foundation was laid, a poor harvest forced the work to pause. The Minister conserved resources and encouraged farming. The following year brought abundant harvest. "Now," said the Minister, "we may employ the people's strength." He consulted the old records, mobilized workers, fixed a deadline, and the fortress rose. From the ninth month, day Jiashen of autumn in the year Wuwei, through the eleventh month, day Wuren of winter—such was the span of the work. In planning and execution, it embodied the wisdom of the Spring and Autumn records concerning fortified cities and defensive works.

    The fortress stands one ren and four chi in height, is seventeen chi broad, and measures five hundred ninety-four paces and three chi in circumference. Along the walls, at intervals of two chi, crenellations were set, each equipped with shield and spear, flags raised high, with arrows and stones placed upon them. Defenders maintain vigilance day and night. From afar it appears steep and formidable; draw near and it stands majestic, sheer and impregnable. It is ringed with a water-filled moat, blocked by drawbridges, embracing mountains and rivers in its expanse—a grand design of noble scope.

    The eastern gate was named Yuanren, the southern Huili, the western Huaiyi, and the northern Yongzhi—names that honored the virtues fitting each direction, conveying both might and moral worth. Within the fortress, the Hall of Righteousness and the House of Plenty were built to store provisions. Formerly, all supplies came from distant places, taking two days and nights to reach the garrison, exhausting both men and beasts—a considerable hardship. Now all was remedied. Coastal counties established storage pits within the walls. When danger threatened, people brought wives and children inside; when it passed, they returned to their fields and pursued their labors without interruption. Such foresight was indeed precise. Should alarm arise, the garrison can respond without stirring, prepared for every contingency.

    When word of this reached the throne, the King praised it highly and bestowed gifts of silk and ceremony. Mencius said, "Heaven's timing is not equal to earth's advantage; earth's advantage is not equal to human harmony." Now, the work began when the dragon star appeared, and was completed by winter solstice—surely Heaven's timing was obtained. The fortress transforms flat ground into defensible terrain, as formidable as controlling the Xiao and Han passes—surely earth's advantage was obtained. The work gathered strength for three months without disrupting livelihood—surely human harmony was obtained. With all three secured, the people sing and dance, honoring the Minister's grace for all time.

    As for the various overseers and supervisors of the work, I have not troubled to record them all. Though this account is plain, it preserves the facts and celebrates the Minister's achievement. In this, I too have played a part.
  footnotes:
    - The dragon star (龍星) refers to the beginning of spring according to the traditional lunar calendar—an auspicious time to commence construction.
    - The Xiao and Han passes (崤函) are legendary strategic fortifications, representing impregnable defensive positions.
    - 'The four gate names carry symbolic meaning: Yuanren (元仁) suggests primordial benevolence; Huili (會禮) embodies the convergence of propriety; Huaiyi (懷義) contains righteousness; Yongzhi (勇智) unites courage and wisdom.'
